# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kd-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] In computer science, a **ball tree**, **balltree** or **metric tree**, is a space partitioning data structure for organizing points in a multi-dimensional space.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] A ball tree partitions data points into a nested set of balls.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] The resulting data structure has characteristics that make it useful for a number of applications, most notably nearest neighbor search.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] A ball tree is a binary tree in which every node defines a D-dimensional ball containing a subset of the points to be searched.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Each internal node of the tree partitions the data points into two disjoint sets which are associated with different balls.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] While the balls themselves may intersect, each point is assigned to one or the other ball in the partition according to its distance from the ball's center.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Each leaf node in the tree defines a ball and enumerates all data points inside that ball.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Each node in the tree defines the smallest ball that contains all data points in its subtree.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] This gives rise to the useful property that, for a given test point t outside the ball, the distance to any point in a ball B in the tree is greater than or equal to the distance from t to the surface of the ball.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Where $D^{B}(t)$ is the minimum possible distance from any point in the ball B to some point t.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Ball-trees are related to the M-tree, but only support binary splits, whereas in the M-tree each level splits m to $2m$ fold, thus leading to a shallower tree structure, therefore need fewer distance computations, which usually yields faster queries.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Furthermore, M-trees can better be stored on disk, which is organized in pages.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] The M-tree also keeps the distances from the parent node precomputed to speed up queries.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Vantage-point trees are also similar, but they binary split into one ball, and the remaining data, instead of using two balls.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] A number of ball tree construction algorithms are available.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] The goal of such an algorithm is to produce a tree that will efficiently support queries of the desired type (e.g. nearest-neighbor) in the average case.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] The specific criteria of an ideal tree will depend on the type of question being answered and the distribution of the underlying data.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] However, a generally applicable measure of an efficient tree is one that minimizes the total volume of its internal nodes.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Given the varied distributions of real-world data sets, this is a difficult task, but there are several heuristics that partition the data well in practice.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] In general, there is a tradeoff between the cost of constructing a tree and the efficiency achieved by this metric.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] This section briefly describes the simplest of these algorithms.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] A more in-depth discussion of five algorithms was given by Stephen Omohundro.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] The simplest such procedure is termed the "*k*-d Construction Algorithm", by analogy with the process used to construct *k*-d trees.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] This is an offline algorithm, that is, an algorithm that operates on the entire data set at once.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] The tree is built top-down by recursively splitting the data points into two sets.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Splits are chosen along the single dimension with the greatest spread of points, with the sets partitioned by the median value of all points along that dimension.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Finding the split for each internal node requires linear time in the number of samples contained in that node, yielding an algorithm with time complexity $O(n\,\log \,n)$ , where *n* is the number of data points.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] An important application of ball trees is expediting nearest neighbor search queries, in which the objective is to find the k points in the tree that are closest to a given test point by some distance metric (e.g.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] A simple search algorithm, sometimes called KNS1, exploits the distance property of the ball tree.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] In particular, if the algorithm is searching the data structure with a test point *t*, and has already seen some point *p* that is closest to *t* among the points encountered so far, then any subtree whose ball is further from *t* than *p* can be ignored for the rest of the search.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] The ball tree nearest-neighbor algorithm examines nodes in depth-first order, starting at the root.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] During the search, the algorithm maintains a max-first priority queue (often implemented with a heap), denoted *Q* here, of the k nearest points encountered so far.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] If *B* is a leaf node, scan through every point enumerated in *B* and update the nearest-neighbor queue appropriately.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] If *B* is an internal node, call the algorithm recursively on *B'*s two children, searching the child whose center is closer to *t* first.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Return the queue after each of these calls has updated it in turn.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] Performing the recursive search in the order described in point 3 above increases likelihood that the further child will be pruned entirely during the search.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] In comparison with several other data structures, ball trees have been shown to perform fairly well on the nearest-neighbor search problem, particularly as their number of dimensions grows.
[src:kd-tree/ball-tree] However, the best nearest-neighbor data structure for a given application will depend on the dimensionality, number of data points, and underlying structure of the data.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] An **implicit *k*-d tree** is a *k*-d tree defined implicitly above a rectilinear grid.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Its split planes' positions and orientations are not given explicitly but implicitly by some recursive splitting-function defined on the hyperrectangles belonging to the tree's nodes.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Each inner node's split plane is positioned on a grid plane of the underlying grid, partitioning the node's grid into two subgrids.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] The terms "min/max *k*-d tree" and "implicit *k*-d tree" are sometimes mixed up.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] This is because the first publication using the term "implicit *k*-d tree" did actually use explicit min/max *k*-d trees but referred to them as "implicit *k*-d trees" to indicate that they may be used to ray trace implicitly given iso surfaces.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Nevertheless, this publication used also slim *k*-d trees which are a subset of the implicit *k*-d trees with the restriction that they can only be built over integer hyperrectangles with sidelengths that are powers of two.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] In the 00s, implicit *k*-d trees as defined here were introduced, with applications in computer graphics.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] As it is possible to assign attributes to implicit *k*-d tree nodes, one may refer to an implicit *k*-d tree which has min/max values assigned to its nodes as an "implicit min/max *k*-d tree".
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Implicit *k*-d trees are generally not constructed explicitly.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] When accessing a node, its split plane orientation and position are evaluated using the specific splitting-function defining the tree.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Different splitting-functions may result in different trees for the same underlying grid.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Splitting-functions may be adapted to special purposes.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Underneath two specifications of special splitting-function classes.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] A complete splitting function is for example the **grid median splitting-function**.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] It creates fairly balanced implicit *k*-d trees by using *k*-dimensional integer hyperrectangles *hyprec[2][k]* belonging to each node of the implicit *k*-d tree.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] The hyperrectangles define which gridcells of the rectilinear grid belong to their corresponding node.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] If the volume of this hyperrectangle equals one, the corresponding node is a single grid cell and is therefore not further subdivided and marked as leaf node.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Otherwise the hyperrectangle's longest extent is chosen as orientation *o*.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] The corresponding split plane *p* is positioned onto the grid plane that is closest to the hyperrectangle's grid median along that orientation.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] An advantage of implicit *k*-d trees is that their split plane's orientations and positions need not to be stored explicitly.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] But some applications require besides the split plane's orientations and positions further attributes at the inner tree nodes.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] These attributes may be for example single bits or single scalar values, defining if the subgrids belonging to the nodes are of interest or not.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] For complete implicit *k*-d trees it is possible to pre-allocate a correctly sized array of attributes and to assign each inner node of the tree to a unique element in that allocated array.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] The amount of gridcells in the grid is equal the volume of the integer hyperrectangle belonging to the grid.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] As a complete implicit *k*-d tree has one inner node less than grid cells, it is known in advance how many attributes need to be stored.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] The relation "*Volume of integer hyperrectangle to inner nodes*" defines together with the complete splitting-function a recursive formula assigning to each split plane a unique element in the allocated array.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] The corresponding algorithm is given in C-pseudo code underneath.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] It is worth mentioning that this algorithm works for all rectilinear grids.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] The corresponding integer hyperrectangle does not necessarily have to have sidelengths that are powers of two.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Implicit max-*k*-d trees are used for ray casting isosurfaces/MIP (maximum intensity projection).
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] The attribute assigned to each inner node is the maximal scalar value given in the subgrid belonging to the node.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Nodes are not traversed if their scalar values are smaller than the searched iso-value/current maximum intensity along the ray.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] The low storage requirements of the implicit max *k*d-tree and the favorable visualization complexity of ray casting allow to ray cast (and even change the isosurface for) very large scalar fields at interactive framerates on commodity PCs.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Similarly an implicit min/max kd-tree may be used to efficiently evaluate queries such as terrain line of sight.
[src:kd-tree/implicit-k-d-tree] Given an implicit *k*-d tree spanned over a *k*-dimensional grid with *n* gridcells.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In computer science, a ***k*-d tree** (short for *k-dimensional tree*) is a space-partitioning data structure for organizing points in a *k*-dimensional space.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] K-dimensional is that which concerns exactly k orthogonal axes or a space of any number of dimensions.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The *k*-d tree is a binary tree in which *every* node is a *k*-dimensional point.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Every non-leaf node can be thought of as implicitly generating a splitting hyperplane that divides the space into two parts, known as half-spaces.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Points to the left of this hyperplane are represented by the left subtree of that node and points to the right of the hyperplane are represented by the right subtree.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The hyperplane direction is chosen in the following way: every node in the tree is associated with one of the *k* dimensions, with the hyperplane perpendicular to that dimension's axis.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] So, for example, if for a particular split the "x" axis is chosen, all points in the subtree with a smaller "x" value than the node will appear in the left subtree and all points with a larger "x" value will be in the right subtree.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In such a case, the hyperplane would be set by the x value of the point, and its normal would be the unit x-axis.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Since there are many possible ways to choose axis-aligned splitting planes, there are many different ways to construct *k*-d trees.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] This method leads to a balanced *k*-d tree, in which each leaf node is approximately the same distance from the root.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] However, balanced trees are not necessarily optimal for all applications.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Note that it is not *required* to select the median point.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In the case where median points are not selected, there is no guarantee that the tree will be balanced.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] To avoid coding a complex $O(n)$ median-finding algorithm or using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as heapsort or mergesort to sort all *n* points, a popular practice is to sort a *fixed* number of *randomly* *selected* points, and use the median of those points to serve as the splitting plane.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In practice, this technique often results in nicely balanced trees.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Given a list of *n* points, the following algorithm uses a median-finding sort to construct a balanced *k*-d tree containing those points.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] It is common that points "after" the median include only the ones that are strictly greater than the median in the current dimension.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] For points that lie on the median in the current dimension, it is possible to define a function that compares them in all dimensions.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In some cases, it is acceptable to let points equal to the median lie on one side of the median, for example, by splitting the points into a "lesser than" subset and a "greater than or equal to" subset.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] This algorithm creates the invariant that for any node, all the nodes in the left subtree are on one side of a splitting plane, and all the nodes in the right subtree are on the other side.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Points that lie on the splitting plane may appear on either side.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The splitting plane of a node goes through the point associated with that node (referred to in the code as *node.location*).
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Alternative algorithms for building a balanced *k*-d tree presort the data prior to building the tree.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Then, they maintain the order of the presort during tree construction and hence eliminate the costly step of finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Two such algorithms build a balanced *k*-d tree to sort triangles in order to improve the execution time of ray tracing for three-dimensional computer graphics.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] These algorithms presort *n* triangles prior to building the *k*-d tree, then build the tree in $O(n\log n)$ time in the best case.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] An algorithm that builds a balanced *k*-d tree to sort points has a worst-case complexity of $O(kn\log(n))$ .
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] This algorithm presorts *n* points in each of *k* dimensions using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as Heapsort or Mergesort prior to building the tree.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] It then maintains the order of these *k* presorts during tree construction and thereby avoids finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] One adds a new point to a *k*-d tree in the same way as one adds an element to any other search tree.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] First, traverse the tree, starting from the root and moving to either the left or the right child depending on whether the point to be inserted is on the "left" or "right" side of the splitting plane.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Once you get to the node under which the child should be located, add the new point as either the left or right child of the leaf node, again depending on which side of the node's splitting plane contains the new node.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Adding points in this manner can cause the tree to become unbalanced, leading to decreased tree performance.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The rate of tree performance degradation is dependent upon the spatial distribution of tree points being added, and the number of points added in relation to the tree size.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] If a tree becomes too unbalanced, it may need to be re-balanced to restore the performance of queries that rely on the tree balancing, such as nearest neighbour searching.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] To remove a point from an existing *k*-d tree without breaking the invariant, the easiest way is to form the set of all nodes and leaves from the children of the target node and recreate that part of the tree.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Another approach is to find a replacement for the point removed.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] First, find the node R that contains the point to be removed.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] For the base case, where R is a leaf node, no replacement is required.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] For the general case, find a replacement point, say p , from the subtree rooted at R .
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] For finding a replacement point, if R discriminates on x (say) and R has a right child, find the point with the minimum x value from the subtree rooted at the right child.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Otherwise, find the point with the maximum x value from the subtree rooted at the left child.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Balancing a *k*-d tree requires care because *k*-d trees are sorted in multiple dimensions, so the tree-rotation technique cannot be used to balance them as this may break the invariant.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Several variants of balanced *k*-d trees exist.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] They include divided *k*-d tree, pseudo *k*-d tree, K-D-B-tree, hB-tree and Bkd-tree.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Many of these variants are adaptive k-d trees.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour search (NN) algorithm aims to find the point in the tree that is nearest to a given input point.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] This search can be done efficiently by using the tree properties to quickly eliminate large portions of the search space.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Once the algorithm reaches a leaf node, it checks the node point and if the distance is better than the "current best", that node point is saved as the "current best".
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The algorithm checks whether there could be any points on the other side of the splitting plane that are closer to the search point than the current best.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In concept, this is done by intersecting the splitting hyperplane with a hypersphere around the search point that has a radius equal to the current nearest distance.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Since the hyperplanes are all axis-aligned this is implemented as a simple comparison to see whether the distance between the splitting coordinate of the search point and current node is less than the distance (overall coordinates) from the search point to the current best.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] If the hypersphere doesn't intersect the splitting plane, then the algorithm continues walking up the tree, and the entire branch on the other side of that node is eliminated.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] When the algorithm finishes this process for the root node, then the search is complete.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Generally the algorithm uses squared distances for comparison to avoid computing square roots.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Additionally, it can save computation by holding the squared current best distance in a variable for comparison.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The algorithm can be extended in several ways by simple modifications.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] It can provide the *k* nearest neighbours to a point by maintaining *k* current bests instead of just one.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] A branch is only eliminated when *k* points have been found and the branch cannot have points closer than any of the *k* current bests.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] It can also be converted to an approximation algorithm to run faster.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] For example, approximate nearest neighbour searching can be achieved by simply setting an upper bound on the number of points to examine in the tree or by interrupting the search process based upon a real time clock (which may be more appropriate in hardware implementations).
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour for points that are already in the tree can be achieved by not updating the refinement for nodes that give zero distance.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] As a result, this has the downside of discarding points that are not unique but are co-located with the original search point.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Approximate nearest neighbour is useful in real-time applications such as robotics due to the significant speed increase gained by not searching for the best point exhaustively.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] One of its implementations is best-bin-first search.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] A range search searches for ranges of parameters.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] For example, if a tree is storing values corresponding to income and age, then a range search might be something like looking for all members of the tree which have an age between 20 and 50 years and an income between 50,000 and 80,000.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Since k-d trees divide the range of a domain in half at each level of the tree, they are useful for performing range searches.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Analyses of binary search trees has found that the worst case time for range search in a *k*-dimensional *k*-d tree containing *n* nodes is given by the following equation.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In low-dimensional spaces, the nearest point is an $O(\log(n))$ operation on average, in the case of randomly distributed points, although analysis in general is tricky.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In high-dimensional spaces, the curse of dimensionality causes the algorithm to need to visit many more branches than in lower-dimensional spaces.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In particular, when the number of points is only slightly higher than the number of dimensions, the algorithm is only slightly better than a linear search of all of the points.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] As a general rule, if the dimensionality is *k*, the number of points in the data, *n*, should be $n\gg 2^{k}$ .
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Otherwise, when *k*-d trees are used with high-dimensional data, most of the points in the tree will be evaluated and the efficiency is no better than exhaustive search, and, if a good-enough fast answer is required, approximate nearest-neighbour methods should be used instead.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] (In the worst case, consider a cloud of points distributed on the surface of a sphere centered at the origin.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] This may result in a nearest neighbor search failing to return a nearest neighbor, which means no points are within this maximum distance from the query point.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Instead of points, a *k*-d tree can also contain rectangles or hyperrectangles.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Thus range search becomes the problem of returning all rectangles intersecting the search rectangle.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The tree is constructed the usual way with all the rectangles at the leaves.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] In an orthogonal range search, the *opposite* coordinate is used when comparing against the median.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] For example, if the current level is split along xhigh, we check the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] If the median is less than the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle, then no rectangle in the left branch can ever intersect with the search rectangle and so can be pruned.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Otherwise both branches should be traversed.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] See also interval tree, which is a 1-dimensional special case.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] It is also possible to define a *k*-d tree with points stored solely in leaves.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] This form of *k*-d tree allows a variety of split mechanics other than the standard median split.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] The midpoint splitting rule selects on the middle of the longest axis of the space being searched, regardless of the distribution of points.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] This guarantees that the aspect ratio will be at most 2:1, but the depth is dependent on the distribution of points.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] A variation, called sliding-midpoint, only splits on the middle if there are points on both sides of the split.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Otherwise, it splits on point nearest to the middle.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Maneewongvatana and Mount show that this offers "good enough" performance on common data sets.
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Using sliding-midpoint, an approximate nearest neighbour query can be answered in $O\left({\tfrac {1}{{\epsilon \ }^{d}}}\log n\right)$ .
[src:kd-tree/k-d-tree] Approximate range counting can be answered in $O\left(\log n+{\left({\tfrac {1}{\epsilon \ }}\right)}^{d}\right)$ with this method.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In high-dimensional spaces, tree indexing structures become useless because an increasing percentage of the nodes need to be examined anyway.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] To speed up linear search, a compressed version of the feature vectors stored in RAM is used to prefilter the datasets in a first run.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The final candidates are determined in a second stage using the uncompressed data from the disk for distance calculation.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The VA-file approach is a special case of a compression based search, where each feature component is compressed uniformly and independently.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The optimal compression technique in multidimensional spaces is Vector Quantization (VQ), implemented through clustering.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The database is clustered and the most "promising" clusters are retrieved.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Huge gains over VA-File, tree-based indexes and sequential scan have been observed.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Also note the parallels between clustering and LSH.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] There are numerous variants of the NNS problem and the two most well-known are the *k*-nearest neighbor search and the ε-approximate nearest neighbor search.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In some applications it may be acceptable to retrieve a "good guess" of the nearest neighbor.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In those cases, we can use an algorithm which doesn't guarantee to return the actual nearest neighbor in every case, in return for improved speed or memory savings.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Often such an algorithm will find the nearest neighbor in a majority of cases, but this depends strongly on the dataset being queried.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Algorithms that support the approximate nearest neighbor search include locality-sensitive hashing, best bin first and balanced box-decomposition tree based search.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Nearest neighbor distance ratio does not apply the threshold on the direct distance from the original point to the challenger neighbor but on a ratio of it depending on the distance to the previous neighbor.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] It is used in CBIR to retrieve pictures through a "query by example" using the similarity between local features.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] More generally it is involved in several matching problems.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Fixed-radius near neighbors is the problem where one wants to efficiently find all points given in Euclidean space within a given fixed distance from a specified point.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance is assumed to be fixed, but the query point is arbitrary.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] For some applications (e.g. entropy estimation), we may have *N* data-points and wish to know which is the nearest neighbor *for every one of those N points*.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This could, of course, be achieved by running a nearest-neighbor search once for every point, but an improved strategy would be an algorithm that exploits the information redundancy between these *N* queries to produce a more efficient search.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] As a simple example: when we find the distance from point *X* to point *Y*, that also tells us the distance from point *Y* to point *X*, so the same calculation can be reused in two different queries.
[src:kd-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Given a fixed dimension, a semi-definite positive norm (thereby including every Lp norm), and *n* points in this space, the nearest neighbour of every point can be found in *O*(*n* log *n*) time and the *m* nearest neighbours of every point can be found in *O*(*mn* log *n*) time.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] In geometry, **space partitioning** is the process of dividing an entire space (usually a Euclidean space) into two or more disjoint subsets (see also partition of a set).
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] In other words, space partitioning divides a space into non-overlapping regions.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Any point in the space can then be identified to lie in exactly one of the regions.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Space-partitioning systems are often hierarchical, meaning that a space (or a region of space) is divided into several regions, and then the same space-partitioning system is recursively applied to each of the regions thus created.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] The regions can be organized into a tree, called a **space-partitioning tree**.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Most space-partitioning systems use planes (or, in higher dimensions, hyperplanes) to divide space: points on one side of the plane form one region, and points on the other side form another.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Points exactly on the plane are usually arbitrarily assigned to one or the other side.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Recursively partitioning space using planes in this way produces a BSP tree, one of the most common forms of space partitioning.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Space partitioning is particularly important in computer graphics, especially heavily used in ray tracing, where it is frequently used to organize the objects in a virtual scene.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] A typical scene may contain millions of polygons.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Performing a ray/polygon intersection test with each would be a very computationally expensive task.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Space partitioning is also often used in scanline algorithms to eliminate the polygons out of the camera's viewing frustum, limiting the number of polygons processed by the pipeline.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] There is also a usage in collision detection: determining whether two objects are close to each other can be much faster using space partitioning.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] In integrated circuit design, an important step is design rule check.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] This step ensures that the completed design is manufacturable.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] The check involves rules that specify widths and spacings and other geometry patterns.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] A modern design can have billions of polygons that represent wires and transistors.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Efficient checking relies heavily on geometry query.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] For example, a rule may specify that any polygon must be at least *n* nanometers from any other polygon.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] This is converted into a geometry query by enlarging a polygon by *n/2* at all sides and query to find all intersecting polygons.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] The number of components in a space partition plays a central role in some results in probability theory.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] There are many studies and applications where Geographical Spatial Reality is partitioned by hydrological criteria, administrative criteria, mathematical criteria or many others.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] In the context of cartography and GIS - Geographic Information System, is common to identify cells of the partition by standard codes.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] For example the for HUC code identifying hydrographical basins and sub-basins, ISO 3166-2 codes identifying countries and its subdivisions, or arbitrary DGGs - discrete global grids identifying quadrants or locations.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Suppose the n-dimensional Euclidean space is partitioned by r hyperplanes that are $(n-1)$ -dimensional.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] What is the number of components in the partition?
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] The largest number of components is attained when the hyperplanes are in general position, i.e, no two are parallel and no three have the same intersection.
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] Denote this maximum number of components by $Comp(n,r)$ .
[src:kd-tree/space-partitioning] perpendicular hyperplanes; each additional hyperplane divides each existing component to 2).
